  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Understand the DOCG Hierarchy for Quality Selection</strong> - When comparing prosecco options, prioritize Conegliano Valdobbiadene DOCG and Asolo DOCG over basic Prosecco DOC. The DOCG wines from these historic hillside zones offer superior concentration, minerality, and complexity due to steep vineyards with calcareous soils. Expect to pay 2-3 times more, but you'll taste the difference in their elegant perlage, longer finish, and distinctive white flower aromatics that basic DOC proseccos simply cannot achieve.</li>

  <li><strong>Decode Sugar Levels to Match Your Preference</strong> - Prosecco's residual sugar dramatically affects how different bottles stack up. Brut Nature (0-3g/L) showcases pure Glera character with crisp green apple and citrus, while Extra Dry (12-17g/L) offers crowd-pleasing roundness with honeyed pear notes. Dry proseccos (17-32g/L) work beautifully with spicy Asian cuisine, but avoid them for aperitifs where their sweetness can overwhelm. Most premium producers favor Brut (6-12g/L) as the sweet spot for food versatility.</li>

  <li><strong>Serving Temperature is Critical for Proper Comparison</strong> - Serve all proseccos at exactly 42-46°F (6-8°C) to fairly evaluate how options stack up. Higher-quality DOCG proseccos maintain their complexity even when slightly warmer, while basic DOC versions become flabby and lose their refreshing edge above 50°F. Chill bottles for 3-4 hours in refrigerator or 20-30 minutes in ice bucket. Over-chilling below 40°F masks the delicate Glera aromatics that distinguish superior bottles.</li>

  <li><strong>Never Decant Prosecco - Preserve the Perlage</strong> - Unlike still wines, prosecco should never be decanted as it destroys the carefully crafted mousse that defines quality. The persistent, fine bubbles in premium proseccos result from secondary fermentation in pressurized tanks (Charmat method) and dissipate rapidly when exposed to air. Pour directly into glasses, filling them one-third full first, then topping off to preserve maximum effervescence and allow proper comparison of bubble quality between different bottles.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Tulip-Shaped Flutes for Accurate Evaluation</strong> - Use tall, narrow tulip flutes rather than coupes when comparing prosecco options. The flute's shape concentrates aromatics and preserves carbonation longer, allowing you to properly assess the delicate white peach, green apple, and acacia honey notes that separate premium bottles from basic ones. Avoid wide glasses that cause rapid bubble loss and prevent you from detecting the subtle mineral differences between Conegliano and Valdobbiadene subzones.</li>

  <li><strong>Prosecco Ages Differently Than Champagne</strong> - Most proseccos are designed for immediate consumption and don't improve with cellaring. However, premium DOCG bottles can develop interesting honey and brioche notes over 2-3 years if stored at 50-55°F with consistent humidity. Vintage-dated proseccos show more aging potential than non-vintage blends. Basic DOC proseccos should be consumed within 12-18 months of purchase, while superiore DOCG can hold for 3-5 years, making storage timeline crucial when stacking up different investment levels.</li>

  <li><strong>Timing Matters for Peak Performance</strong> - Open prosecco bottles immediately before serving for optimal comparison. Unlike Champagne, prosecco's Charmat method produces more delicate bubbles that dissipate quickly once opened. The best tasting window is within the first 30-45 minutes after opening. If comparing multiple bottles, use a champagne stopper to preserve carbonation between tastings. Premium DOCG proseccos maintain their character longer than basic versions, but even the finest bottles lose their signature vivacity after 2-3 hours of exposure.</li>

  <li><strong>Recognize Authentic Glera Expression</strong> - When evaluating how different prosecco options stack up, look for authentic Glera grape characteristics: white flowers (acacia), green fruits (Granny Smith apple, lime zest), and subtle herbs (sage, white pepper). Cheap proseccos often taste generic or overly sweet, masking Glera's natural elegance. Premium bottles from historic zones express terroir through mineral notes - chalk and wet stone from Valdobbiadene's steep slopes, or the more delicate floral profile from Asolo's volcanic soils. Avoid bottles with artificial fruit flavors or excessive residual sugar that obscure varietal character.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically across quality levels, with most styles designed for immediate enjoyment rather than long-term cellaring. Understanding these differences helps maximize your investment in premium bottles.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 12-18 months of purchase. These wines rely on primary fruit flavors and lose their vibrant apple and pear notes quickly. <strong>Prosecco DOCG</strong> from Conegliano-Valdobbiadene can develop for 2-3 years, with premium cuvées showing potential for 4-5 years when properly stored.</p>

<p><strong>Cartizze</strong> and vintage Prosecco represent the pinnacle of aging potential. Top producers like Nino Franco's "Primo Franco" or Bisol's "Cartizze" can evolve gracefully for 5-8 years, developing honeyed complexity while retaining freshness.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>

<p>Fresh Prosecco exhibits bright citrus and green apple flavors with floral notes. After 2-3 years, quality examples develop <strong>autolytic character</strong>—subtle bread crust and almond notes from extended lees contact. The fruit shifts from primary to secondary, showing dried pear and quince complexity.</p>

<p>Peak drinking windows: DOC within 2 years, DOCG at 2-4 years, and premium vintage expressions at 3-6 years.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store Prosecco at consistent <strong>50-55°F (10-13°C)</strong> with 70% humidity. Unlike still wines, sparkling wines should remain upright for short-term storage (under 6 months) to minimize wine-cork contact, then horizontal for longer aging.</p>

<h3>Aging vs Spoilage Signs</h3>

<p>Proper aging shows <strong>integrated bubbles</strong>, deeper golden color, and evolved aromatics maintaining freshness. Spoilage presents as browning, flat bubbles, oxidized apple/sherry notes, or vinegar aromas. Quality Prosecco retains its essential vibrancy even when mature.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Prosecco DOC and Prosecco DOCG?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco DOCG comes from the prestigious Conegliano Valdobbiadene and Asolo zones, offering more concentrated flavors and finer bubbles due to steeper hillside vineyards and stricter production rules. Prosecco DOC covers a broader area across Veneto and Friuli, typically offering lighter, more accessible wines at lower prices. The DOCG designation generally commands 30-50% higher prices but delivers noticeably more complexity and elegance.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do Brut, Extra Dry, and Dry Prosecco compare in sweetness?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Counterintuitively, "Dry" Prosecco is actually the sweetest style with 17-32g/L residual sugar, while "Extra Dry" falls in the middle at 12-17g/L, and "Brut" is the driest at under 12g/L. Most premium producers focus on Brut and Extra Dry styles, as these better showcase the wine's natural acidity and fruit character. Extra Dry remains the most popular style in Italy, offering a perfect balance for aperitivo culture.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is spending $25+ on premium Prosecco worth it compared to $12 bottles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Proseccos from top producers like Bisol, Nino Franco, or Ruggeri offer significantly finer bubbles, more complex aromatics, and better integration of acidity due to hand-harvesting and longer lees aging. While $12 bottles serve well for casual drinking and mixing, the $20-30 range delivers restaurant-quality wine with distinct terroir expression. The jump from $30 to $50+ shows diminishing returns unless you're seeking rare single-vineyard expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Prosecco styles work best for different occasions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Brut Prosecco excels with raw seafood and as an aperitif due to its crisp acidity, while Extra Dry pairs beautifully with fruit-forward appetizers and light pasta dishes. Dry Prosecco works best with spicy Asian cuisine or as a dessert wine with fresh fruit. For celebrations, choose DOCG expressions, while DOC versions are perfect for casual entertaining and Prosecco cocktails like Aperol Spritzes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes when choosing Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is buying Prosecco too far in advance—unlike Champagne, most Proseccos are meant for immediate consumption and lose their fresh, vibrant character within 2-3 years. Another mistake is storing opened bottles for more than 24 hours even with stoppers, as the Charmat method creates less persistent bubbles than traditional method sparkling wines. Always check the vintage date and choose the most recent available.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How does Franciacorta compare to Prosecco for value?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Franciacorta, made using the traditional Champagne method, offers more complexity and aging potential but typically costs 2-3 times more than comparable Prosecco. While Prosecco delivers immediate fruit-forward pleasure and food versatility, Franciacorta provides deeper yeasty notes and finer bubbles that justify the premium for special occasions. For everyday drinking and value, Prosecco wins; for cellar-worthy Italian sparkling wine, Franciacorta takes the lead.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should beginners start with Prosecco DOC or invest in DOCG bottles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Wine newcomers should start with quality Prosecco DOC from established producers like Villa Sandi or Zonin to understand the grape's characteristic green apple and white flower notes without the premium price. Once familiar with the style, upgrading to DOCG expressions from producers like Adami or Col Vetoraz will reveal the additional complexity and refinement that terroir and stricter standards provide. This progression helps develop palate awareness while managing costs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semiberal text-wine-700 mb-2">How long does Prosecco stay fresh after opening compared to Champagne?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco typically maintains its effervescence for 12-24 hours after opening with a proper sparkling wine stopper, while Champagne can last 2-3 days due to its traditional method production creating more persistent bubbles. The Charmat method used for Prosecco creates larger, less stable bubbles that dissipate more quickly. For best results, consume opened Prosecco within 24 hours and store it in the refrigerator with a quality closure system.</p>
  </div>
</div>

